  "prompt": "How many colors and hues are distinguishable to the human eye?",
  "response": "The human eye can distinguish around 10 million different colors. This ability is due to the presence of three types of cone cells in the retina, which are sensitive to different wavelengths of light: short (S), medium (M), and long (L), corresponding roughly to blue, green, and red regions of the spectrum.\n\nAs for hues, which are a component of color associated with the wavelength of light, the human eye can perceive approximately 150 distinct hues. This perception is influenced by the combination of different responses from the cone cells, allowing us to experience a wide variety of colors through the mixing of primary colors (red, green, and blue), along with their varying intensities and saturation levels.\n\nThese numbers can vary slightly depending on individual differences in vision and the precise way color discrimination is measured.",
